In [10]: 
def select_columns(df, min_r=.5e-1):
    """ Select out columns with highest covariance with target sample
    
    Parameters:
    -----------
    df : pandas.DataFrame
        DataFrame containing the target and parameter data
    min_r : float, int
        minimum covariance to specify if a column should be used
        
    Returns:
    --------
    good_columns : list
        the selected columns from the DataFram
        
    Outputs:
    --------
    plot of all 254 parameters vs the target sample
    
    """
    
    good_columns = []

    fig = plt.figure(figsize=(30, 30))
    n_plots = df.shape[1]-1
    n = int(np.sqrt(n_plots)) + 1
    
    for i, colname in enumerate(df):
        if colname == 'target':
            continue

        ax = fig.add_subplot(n, n, i)

        ydata = df['target']
        #-- fill in missing data with 0's. 
        xdata = df[colname].fillna(0)

        r, p = pearsonr(xdata, ydata)
        
        if abs(r) > min_r:
            good_columns.append(colname)
            
            ax.plot(xdata, ydata, 'o', color='b', marker='.')
        else:
            ax.plot(xdata, ydata, 'o', color='grey', marker='.', alpha=.5)

        ax.xaxis.set_ticklabels('')
        ax.yaxis.set_ticklabels('')
        ax.set_title('{}, r:{:3.2e}'.format(i-1, r), color='grey')
        
    fig.suptitle('Parameter covariance with target', fontsize=36)

    fig.savefig('parameters_covariance.png')
    
    return good_columns
In [11]: 
good_columns = select_columns(df)

The plot above displays all 254 parameters plotted against the targets, with the correlation coefficient displayed above each subplot. The subplots that have been grayed out were deemed to have too low of a correlation with the targets to be helpful to the fit. Note that the subplots showing very discrete structures in the X dimension are the integer-encoded string values.

The columns with the largest affect on the outcome of the targets have been selected, but there is still some additional clearning to be done. Any rows in the training set that have missing values could throw off the fit, so they will be discarded.

Fitting the model

After trying multiple models in the scikit-learn package, the GradientBoostingRegressor model has given the most accurate predictions so far, and has been robust against simply memorizing the dataset. Therefore, we'll use this model for the final fit and predictions.

The sections that follow immediately is simply training the model on a subset of the available input data, and using that model to predict and evaluate the remainder of the training dataset.

In [13]: 
#-- Parameters have been chosen to minimize the calculated mean square through an interacitve, 
#-- iterative process.
classifier = ensemble.GradientBoostingRegressor(loss='ls', learning_rate=.07, n_estimators=700)
classifier.fit(sub_data[:3000], sub_targets[:3000])
